WEBVTT

00:44.690 --> 00:46.740
[crunching]

00:55.220 --> 00:57.270
♪

01:10.630 --> 01:12.680
♪

01:23.560 --> 01:25.600
[waves crashing]

01:39.400 --> 01:41.440
[woman laughing in distance]

01:50.190 --> 01:52.240
[breathes deeply]

01:56.850 --> 01:58.290
[woman grunts]

02:05.600 --> 02:07.250
[sighs]

02:11.390 --> 02:12.950
[woman exhales]

02:18.130 --> 02:19.840
[groans]

02:20.040 --> 02:22.660
["[You Don't Know] How Glad
I Am" by Nancy Wilson playing]

02:26.450 --> 02:28.020
♪ My love has no beginning

02:28.220 --> 02:30.240
♪ My love has no end

02:30.440 --> 02:33.110
♪ No front or back,
and my love won't bend ♪

02:33.310 --> 02:35.720
♪ I'm in the middle

02:35.920 --> 02:38.850
- ♪ Lost in a spin
- [tires screech]

02:39.810 --> 02:46.170
♪ Loving you...

02:46.370 --> 02:48.340
[engine rattling]

02:49.560 --> 02:51.180
- [engine backfires]
- ♪ And you don't know

02:51.370 --> 02:53.310
♪ You don't know, you don't
know, you don't know ♪

02:53.510 --> 02:55.870
♪ How glad I am

02:58.700 --> 03:02.010
♪ My love has no bottom,
my love has no top ♪

03:02.210 --> 03:05.010
♪ My love won't rise,
and my love won't drop ♪

03:05.210 --> 03:07.140
♪ I'm in the middle

03:08.140 --> 03:10.050
♪ And I can't stop

03:11.100 --> 03:17.890
♪ Loving you...

03:21.460 --> 03:23.210
♪ And you don't, you don't
know, you don't know ♪

03:23.410 --> 03:27.900
♪ You don't know
how glad I am ♪

03:29.470 --> 03:33.960
♪ I wish I were a poet

03:34.160 --> 03:36.660
♪ So I could express

03:36.850 --> 03:38.570
♪ What I'd

03:38.770 --> 03:42.960
♪ What I'd like to say, yeah

03:43.650 --> 03:47.010
♪ I wish I were an artist ♪

03:47.210 --> 03:50.280
♪ So I could paint a picture

03:50.480 --> 03:52.760
♪ Of how I feel

03:52.960 --> 03:57.490
♪ Of how I feel today, yeah

03:58.800 --> 04:02.070
♪ My love has
no walls on either side ♪

04:02.270 --> 04:04.770
♪ That makes my love
wider than wide ♪

04:04.970 --> 04:06.950
♪ I'm in the middle

04:07.150 --> 04:09.510
♪ And I can't hide

04:10.680 --> 04:17.250
♪ Loving you...

04:18.860 --> 04:20.530
♪ And you don't, you don't
know, you don't know ♪

04:20.720 --> 04:26.780
♪ You don't know
how glad I am ♪

04:27.740 --> 04:30.130
♪ How glad I am

04:31.480 --> 04:33.790
♪ How glad I am

04:34.970 --> 04:37.110
♪ How glad I am

04:37.310 --> 04:38.370
[typewriter keys clacking]

04:38.570 --> 04:39.630
[fading]:
♪ How glad I am...

04:39.830 --> 04:42.720
[overlapping chatter]

04:42.920 --> 04:43.930
MRS. MURRAY:
Eileen.

04:45.540 --> 04:46.420
Eileen!

04:46.620 --> 04:47.420
[phones ringing]

04:47.620 --> 04:49.290
I need form I-37.

04:49.490 --> 04:50.690
- Transfer form?
- No.

04:50.890 --> 04:52.950
Intake. I-37.

04:53.150 --> 04:54.950
Aren't you listening?

04:55.150 --> 04:56.430
She is useless.

04:56.630 --> 04:58.610
MRS. STEVENS: Dr. Frye
still needs to sign it.

04:58.810 --> 05:00.740
He's probably asleep
in his office.

05:00.940 --> 05:02.570
MRS. MURRAY:
Oh, yeah.

05:02.770 --> 05:04.400
Maybe you could go
wake up Dr. Frye.

05:04.590 --> 05:06.090
Blow softly in his ear.

05:06.290 --> 05:07.790
- He loves that.
- [guard chuckles]

05:07.990 --> 05:09.230
MRS. STEVENS:
Leave Eileen alone.

05:09.430 --> 05:10.880
She's tired.

05:11.080 --> 05:12.970
Oh, is that what it is?

05:13.170 --> 05:15.100
I thought maybe it was
that time of the month.

05:15.300 --> 05:17.020
At least I have
a time of the month.

05:17.220 --> 05:18.760
MRS. MURRAY: Oh, yeah.
You know something, honey?

05:18.960 --> 05:20.670
It won't last forever.
You'll be old like us soon.

05:20.870 --> 05:22.670
[buzzer sounds]

05:22.870 --> 05:24.500
[over P.A.]: Mrs. Nelson
to the visiting area, please.

05:24.700 --> 05:26.890
Mrs. Nelson
to the visiting area.

05:29.980 --> 05:32.020
[overlapping chatter]

05:44.770 --> 05:46.820
[overlapping chatter]

05:51.170 --> 05:53.180
INMATE: I'm not gonna fight
with anybody. I told you.

05:53.380 --> 05:54.360
INMATE 2:
How's Mickey doing?

05:54.560 --> 05:55.750
MAN 1:
I'm trying to be good.

05:55.950 --> 05:57.060
WOMAN:
Sit down. Sit down. Sit down.

05:57.260 --> 05:58.320
MAN 1:
Well, it's not my fault...

05:58.520 --> 05:59.670
[chatter continues
indistinctly]

05:59.870 --> 06:02.360
♪

06:17.850 --> 06:19.900
♪

06:26.730 --> 06:28.380
♪

06:40.310 --> 06:41.830
[sighs]

06:45.750 --> 06:48.630
[buzzer sounds]

06:48.830 --> 06:51.750
[indistinct announcement
over P.A.]

06:55.320 --> 06:57.890
[overlapping chatter]

06:59.500 --> 07:01.420
WOMAN:
Maybe I'll see you next time.

07:03.240 --> 07:04.650
[group laughing]

07:04.850 --> 07:06.820
WARDEN: As much as we're
gonna miss the old dog,

07:07.020 --> 07:08.520
I hope you'll all be welcoming

07:08.720 --> 07:10.560
to Dr. Frye's replacement
on Monday.

07:10.760 --> 07:12.390
DR. FRYE:
A fine, fine young doctor.

07:12.590 --> 07:15.400
WARDEN: Yes, well, let's hope
the boys take her seriously.

07:15.600 --> 07:16.660
I'll take her.

07:16.860 --> 07:19.830
- Seriously.
- [laughter]

07:20.030 --> 07:22.270
I think you will be
taking your insulin

07:22.470 --> 07:23.880
and your retirement package.

07:24.080 --> 07:25.270
That'll be enough for you.

07:25.470 --> 07:26.710
DR. FRYE [laughing]:
That's right.

07:26.910 --> 07:29.580
I'll really miss
all the fun around here.

07:29.780 --> 07:31.320
Let's hear it for Dr. Frye.

07:31.520 --> 07:33.330
- [applause]
- WARDEN: Cheers!

07:33.530 --> 07:35.450
♪

07:44.850 --> 07:46.900
♪

07:59.130 --> 08:01.830
BOB:
I see a lot of Anne these days.

08:02.030 --> 08:04.920
COP: Yeah, a lot
of broken hearts out there.

08:05.120 --> 08:06.750
Hey, hon.

08:06.950 --> 08:08.230
Hey.

08:08.430 --> 08:09.480
How's your dad?

08:11.440 --> 08:12.580
Good.

08:12.780 --> 08:13.890
[paper rustling]

08:14.090 --> 08:15.750
You know what? Let me get that.

08:16.490 --> 08:17.800
EILEEN:
Thanks.

08:20.760 --> 08:22.070
[door opens, bell jingles]

08:22.270 --> 08:23.720
♪

08:32.290 --> 08:34.470
MAN: ...want you to go inside
and shut the fuck up!

08:34.670 --> 08:36.220
JIM:
You shut... you shut up!

08:36.410 --> 08:37.780
- MAN 2: Fuck off! Shut up!
- JIM: You shut up!

08:37.980 --> 08:39.480
- MAN: Fucking booze bag!
- JIM: Oh, I'll do...

08:39.680 --> 08:41.440
- I'm gonna have a drink.
- You all right there, chief?

08:41.640 --> 08:43.050
You can fuck right off.

08:43.250 --> 08:45.140
Goddamn Lutherans next door
are the problem, not me.

08:45.340 --> 08:47.230
Nobody's complaining.
We just want to make sure

08:47.430 --> 08:48.620
you're getting home
safe and sound.

08:48.820 --> 08:49.710
JIM:
Nobody's complaining?

08:49.910 --> 08:50.750
- Dad.
- Safe and sound?

08:50.950 --> 08:51.930
Why wouldn't I be safe
and sound?

08:52.130 --> 08:53.360
Dad.

08:53.560 --> 08:54.800
I keep the whole fucking
neighborhood safe and sound.

08:55.000 --> 08:55.580
- What do you know?
- Dad.

08:55.780 --> 08:57.020
E-Eileen, go inside.

08:57.220 --> 08:59.020
- Okay. Dad, look to me.
- Go inside.

08:59.220 --> 09:00.330
Come on. Please. Please.

09:00.530 --> 09:02.110
Hey! You're causing a scene.

09:02.310 --> 09:04.770
JIM: Trust me, Eileen.
Nobody wants nothing with you.

09:04.970 --> 09:06.200
- Okay.
- Mwah!

09:06.400 --> 09:07.810
- Come on. Go inside.
- Mwah!

09:08.010 --> 09:09.550
JIM:
Goddamn Lutherans right there.

09:09.750 --> 09:11.560
Your mother always hated
those people.

09:11.750 --> 09:14.470
- Gosh, let's go inside.
- They can fuck off. Sure.

09:14.670 --> 09:16.210
You can't go around
policing people, Dad.

09:16.410 --> 09:18.820
Who says?
You know who that guy was?

09:19.020 --> 09:20.300
BUCK: We got it all
under control, chief.

09:20.500 --> 09:21.780
You can take it easy. Please.

09:21.980 --> 09:24.000
Take it easy?
Y-You fuckin' take it easy.

09:24.200 --> 09:25.310
EILEEN:
You're not a cop anymore.

09:25.510 --> 09:26.610
Yeah, sure.

09:26.810 --> 09:28.220
I didn't want to retire.
They made me,

09:28.420 --> 09:29.530
'cause I was
too goddamn good at it.

09:29.730 --> 09:30.920
BUCK: Look, I gotta get
back to the station.

09:31.120 --> 09:32.010
Pour me a drink. Good.

09:32.210 --> 09:33.190
Get back to the station, Buck.

09:33.380 --> 09:34.670
Give me my drink.

09:34.860 --> 09:36.540
Just give us a call
if you need anything.

09:36.740 --> 09:38.140
Merry Christmas.

09:39.660 --> 09:41.360
[door closes]

09:44.880 --> 09:47.370
Hey, come here.
What's that smell?

09:47.570 --> 09:48.550
Did you step in something?

09:48.750 --> 09:50.900
No. Why? What do you smell?

09:51.100 --> 09:52.150
I don't know. Roadkill.

09:53.760 --> 09:55.590
Maybe you should
keep your distance.

09:57.460 --> 09:59.170
Yeah, I'll keep my distance.

09:59.370 --> 10:01.340
The fuck you doing?
Put my fucking shoes back on.

10:01.540 --> 10:03.390
But maybe
you should be nicer to me.

10:03.590 --> 10:05.430
No one else is gonna
put up with your shit.

10:05.630 --> 10:07.260
Go then, 'cause I got Joanie.

10:07.460 --> 10:10.180
She wouldn't keep a place
looking like this.

10:10.380 --> 10:12.180
She's a real woman,
your sister.

10:12.380 --> 10:14.100
And she smells like a woman.

10:14.300 --> 10:15.790
She knows how to keep a house!

10:15.990 --> 10:19.230
And she doesn't live here,
and she's married!

10:19.430 --> 10:21.840
Yeah, 'cause she's
not a hanger-on.

10:22.040 --> 10:23.760
And she doesn't want
to talk to you!

10:23.960 --> 10:28.070
Yeah, sure, 'cause she's
made a life of her own.

10:28.270 --> 10:29.930
She's made something
of herself.

10:32.710 --> 10:34.330
Whatever, Dad.

10:34.530 --> 10:36.670
Get a life, Eileen. Get a clue.

10:46.730 --> 10:48.640
[dog barking in distance]

10:54.130 --> 10:56.130
[grunts]

10:57.260 --> 10:59.310
[panting]

11:03.880 --> 11:05.920
[overlapping chatter]

11:11.840 --> 11:13.890
[spoon clinking on glass]

11:19.500 --> 11:21.020
[chatter continues in distance]

11:26.160 --> 11:27.810
[vehicle approaching]

11:31.470 --> 11:33.510
Shit.

11:35.990 --> 11:37.780
[groans]

11:39.300 --> 11:40.830
[huffs]

11:41.030 --> 11:43.050
[car engine idling]

11:43.250 --> 11:44.610
Fuck it.

11:46.880 --> 11:48.920
[engine turns off]

11:50.360 --> 11:52.360
[chatter continues in distance]

12:10.940 --> 12:12.990
[buzzer sounds in distance]

12:17.780 --> 12:19.440
WARDEN:
All right, listen up!

12:19.640 --> 12:21.310
[clears throat]

12:21.510 --> 12:23.360
As you know, in the new year,

12:23.550 --> 12:25.740
we will be up for state review.

12:26.740 --> 12:30.410
So we're gonna be
tightening our procedures

12:30.610 --> 12:36.580
and implementing new strategies
based on some big, new ideas.

12:37.490 --> 12:40.890
And on that note,
this new young lady to my left,

12:41.090 --> 12:43.510
Dr. Miss Rebecca St. John,

12:43.710 --> 12:46.420
is our new prison psychologist.

12:46.620 --> 12:49.990
She's just finished
her doctorate at Radcliffe.

12:50.190 --> 12:51.470
Harvard.

12:51.670 --> 12:53.470
Ah. Harvard.

12:53.670 --> 12:54.950
We may not be Harvard people,

12:55.150 --> 12:57.130
but I think
we can keep up with her,

12:57.330 --> 13:00.440
and hopefully she can
keep up with us

13:00.640 --> 13:02.870
as we keep up with them.

13:03.070 --> 13:05.790
She may be easy on the eyes,
but I assure you,

13:05.990 --> 13:07.660
she is very smart.

13:07.860 --> 13:11.530
[fading]: Ladies, I hope you
show Miss St. John around...

13:11.730 --> 13:13.700
♪

13:26.670 --> 13:28.370
REBECCA:
Say, how much for a glazed?

13:29.330 --> 13:30.810
They're free.

13:31.810 --> 13:33.240
I'm kidding.

13:34.200 --> 13:36.170
I'm Rebecca.

13:36.370 --> 13:37.860
I know.

13:39.200 --> 13:41.480
Say, where can a girl
get freshened up around here?

13:41.680 --> 13:43.000
I can show you.

13:43.200 --> 13:45.130
Sure. Appreciate it.

13:45.330 --> 13:46.480
Can I take your jacket?

13:46.680 --> 13:48.520
Aren't you sweet? Thanks.

13:49.610 --> 13:50.870
This way.

13:52.440 --> 13:53.790
I don't think
I caught your name.

13:53.990 --> 13:55.010
Eileen.

13:55.210 --> 13:57.100
- Morning.
- Morning.

13:57.300 --> 13:58.410
EILEEN:
Where you from?

13:58.610 --> 13:59.670
REBECCA:
Huh?

13:59.870 --> 14:01.240
Oh, I'm from New York
originally.

14:01.440 --> 14:02.800
- Manhattan.
- [sniffs]

14:03.000 --> 14:06.680
Couldn't stand Cambridge.
Way too uptight.

14:06.880 --> 14:08.370
Well, there were a couple
of interesting people,

14:08.570 --> 14:11.120
but, no, I needed a break.

14:11.310 --> 14:12.680
Get some fresh air.

14:12.880 --> 14:14.540
And I love the beach.

14:16.890 --> 14:18.460
All right.

14:19.290 --> 14:20.560
32...

14:20.760 --> 14:22.820
[dial clicking]

14:23.020 --> 14:25.120
24...

14:26.080 --> 14:27.350
...34.

14:27.550 --> 14:28.830
Practically my measurements.

14:29.030 --> 14:31.400
You know, some women
think their figures

14:31.600 --> 14:33.490
are the only thing
that matters.

14:33.680 --> 14:35.700
Honestly, I think
that's kind of pathetic.

14:36.650 --> 14:38.100
I completely agree.

14:38.300 --> 14:40.320
My sister's like that,
and she's not very smart.

14:40.520 --> 14:41.890
Mm, good. Then you and I

14:42.080 --> 14:44.840
have better things to discuss
than our figures.

14:45.040 --> 14:47.720
Although that isn't
the popular opinion,

14:47.920 --> 14:49.020
wouldn't you say?

14:49.220 --> 14:50.750
[scoffs]
I don't care what's popular.

14:51.840 --> 14:53.850
Well, look at you.

14:54.050 --> 14:55.460
A regular Katharine Hepburn.

14:55.660 --> 14:57.640
Rare to meet a young woman
with so much gumption.

14:57.840 --> 14:59.120
I'm like that, too.

14:59.320 --> 15:02.040
I don't give a rat's ass
what people think.

15:02.240 --> 15:03.300
They're probably scared of you.

15:03.500 --> 15:05.120
Moi?

15:06.470 --> 15:08.290
All right. See you around.

15:11.380 --> 15:13.480
- Every year,
- [low chattering]

15:13.680 --> 15:15.310
we hold this special assembly

15:15.510 --> 15:17.790
to celebrate the birth
of Our Lord Jesus Christ.

15:17.990 --> 15:20.010
And every year,
one of you sick bastards

15:20.210 --> 15:21.660
ruins it for the rest of us.

15:21.860 --> 15:26.580
Well, you've disrespected
Christmas for the last time

15:26.780 --> 15:28.710
because this year,
you're gonna sit on your hands,

15:28.910 --> 15:30.720
you're gonna zip your lips.

15:30.920 --> 15:33.110
If I see any of you biting,
kicking, screaming, pushing,

15:33.310 --> 15:35.500
pulling hair,
laughing, moaning,

15:35.700 --> 15:38.460
or I hear one wayward comment,

15:38.660 --> 15:40.640
you're going
straight to the cave.

15:40.840 --> 15:42.900
And now, without further ado,

15:43.100 --> 15:46.560
it is my honor to thank
the people from Mount Olive

15:46.760 --> 15:48.340
who helped me direct
the pageant again this year...

15:48.540 --> 15:50.170
- INMATE: Yay, Mount Olive.
- and present to you

15:50.370 --> 15:52.960
"Christmas in Prison."

15:53.160 --> 15:56.390
[orchestral version
of "Silent Night" playing]

15:56.590 --> 15:58.560
[low chattering continues]

16:04.180 --> 16:05.620
[door opens]

16:05.820 --> 16:07.930
DELUCA: I'm gonna kill someone
on Christmas.

16:08.130 --> 16:09.660
INMATE:
Shut up!

16:10.660 --> 16:12.890
[high heels clicking on floor]

16:13.090 --> 16:14.970
♪

16:17.100 --> 16:19.770
ACTOR:
Oh, what am I to do?

16:19.960 --> 16:21.810
Sentenced for three years
to sit indoors

16:22.010 --> 16:23.990
among boys of my same creed,
plain bad.

16:24.190 --> 16:25.990
- [Deluca laughs]
- So much time to plot

16:26.190 --> 16:28.470
what evildoings I'll undertake
as soon as I get out.

16:28.670 --> 16:30.210
DELUCA:
You want some cake, you fatty?!

16:30.410 --> 16:32.210
ACTOR: In the meantime,
I suppose I could read a book.

16:32.410 --> 16:34.210
DELUCA:
You can't read, motherfucker!

16:34.410 --> 16:36.730
[laughter]

16:39.950 --> 16:41.520
INMATE:
Fucking Shakespeare up here.

16:42.650 --> 16:45.130
[chimes play]

16:48.740 --> 16:50.190
DELUCA:
I'm scrappy right now.

16:50.390 --> 16:52.270
INMATE:
Book of truth!

16:55.140 --> 16:56.370
[chattering continues]

16:56.570 --> 16:57.670
[scattered laughter]

16:57.870 --> 16:59.890
DELUCA:
Oh, look at McAllister.

17:00.090 --> 17:01.110
- Fucking McAllister.
- [laughter]

17:01.310 --> 17:02.850
INMATE:
Hey, nice rack!

17:03.050 --> 17:04.900
[laughter continues]

17:05.100 --> 17:06.510
MARY:
Well, I'm-I'm pretty tired.

17:06.710 --> 17:08.510
Can we rest in that barn
over there?

17:08.710 --> 17:09.990
JOSEPH:
Better than paying for a motel.

17:10.190 --> 17:11.820
MARY:
You're the best, Joseph.

17:12.020 --> 17:13.950
Thank you for taking us here
to be counted in the census.

17:14.150 --> 17:15.080
DELUCA:
Fuck this shit!

17:15.280 --> 17:16.390
- MRS. MURRAY: Guard!
- DELUCA: Wait.

17:16.590 --> 17:17.860
- Wait. Wait, wait.
- GUARD: Hey, grab him.

17:18.950 --> 17:20.090
[Deluca shrieks]

17:20.290 --> 17:23.340
- [inmates clamoring]
- [whistle blowing]

17:24.690 --> 17:26.480
- [siren wailing]
- GUARD: Move back!

17:28.650 --> 17:31.220
[inmates shouting]

17:37.140 --> 17:39.530
- [wailing siren continues]
- [inmates shouting]

17:42.320 --> 17:44.810
GUARD:
All you guys sit down!

17:45.010 --> 17:46.500
Sit the fuck down!

17:48.540 --> 17:49.680
Hey, Bob.

17:49.880 --> 17:50.730
Hey, hon.

17:50.930 --> 17:52.160
This and a pack of Luckies.

17:52.360 --> 17:55.170
Oh! It's a lucky day, huh?

17:55.360 --> 17:56.820
Yeah, the luckiest.

17:57.020 --> 17:59.340
Yup. Cigarettes are great.

17:59.540 --> 18:01.510
[TV playing indistinctly
in other room]

18:02.860 --> 18:04.510
JIM:
Don't light yourself on fire.

18:05.470 --> 18:07.430
[coughs]

18:09.300 --> 18:12.170
[coughing, chuckles]

18:14.130 --> 18:16.400
You're in a good mood,
what's wrong with you?

18:16.600 --> 18:18.410
Nothing's wrong, Dad.

18:18.610 --> 18:20.570
[train whistle blowing
in distance]

18:25.100 --> 18:27.450
You look funny with that thing
in your mouth.

18:29.190 --> 18:31.290
How was your day, Dad?

18:31.490 --> 18:32.890
How was my day?

18:33.850 --> 18:35.030
I don't know.

18:35.230 --> 18:36.860
It was a day, just another day.

18:37.060 --> 18:38.500
What's the point?

18:40.590 --> 18:42.300
My day was a doozy.

18:42.500 --> 18:44.520
Oh, yeah?

18:44.720 --> 18:47.650
A big fight broke out
at the Christmas pageant.

18:47.850 --> 18:50.440
Kid got his collarbone broken,

18:50.640 --> 18:53.440
and I had to do all
this paperwork for the warden.

18:53.640 --> 18:55.910
Don't ash on the floor,
it's tacky.

18:57.910 --> 18:59.660
Anyway...

19:01.180 --> 19:02.710
It was one of those days
you never forget.

19:02.910 --> 19:04.830
Oh, yeah?
Days I'll never forget.

19:05.790 --> 19:07.850
Let me see.

19:08.050 --> 19:10.110
December 16, 1944,

19:10.310 --> 19:13.550
first time I ever held
a dead man's head in my lap.

19:13.750 --> 19:15.940
[exhales]
What a waste.

19:16.140 --> 19:18.410
20 degrees outside and snowing.

19:19.370 --> 19:21.690
Just like it is here.

19:21.890 --> 19:24.250
Don't know why I ever
came back to this place.

19:24.450 --> 19:27.520
Maybe because you had a wife
and two kids.

19:27.720 --> 19:29.250
Maybe.

19:29.950 --> 19:31.130
I love the beach.

19:31.330 --> 19:33.350
Oh, yeah? Good for you.

19:33.550 --> 19:35.480
War kind of ruined beaches
for me.

19:35.680 --> 19:37.830
So what else?

19:38.030 --> 19:40.490
How's that Polk kid?
He talked yet?

19:40.690 --> 19:41.530
Huh?

19:41.730 --> 19:42.880
Polk.

19:43.080 --> 19:44.740
The kid who stabbed
his father...

19:45.830 --> 19:48.750
...who was a good cop,
more or less.

19:51.270 --> 19:53.880
What kind of kid thinks of
killing his father like that?

19:55.360 --> 19:57.160
Stab him in his sleep...

19:57.360 --> 19:58.980
in front of his mother.

20:00.850 --> 20:02.770
Then he just sits down.

20:02.970 --> 20:04.820
Never denies it.

20:05.020 --> 20:07.070
Never says a word
the whole trial.

20:09.380 --> 20:11.030
Psychopathic.

20:15.560 --> 20:17.090
Course I wouldn't
have to worry about you

20:17.290 --> 20:19.000
doing something like that,
now, would I?

20:19.200 --> 20:21.140
'Cause you're a girl.

20:21.340 --> 20:23.220
Can't imagine you with a knife.

20:24.350 --> 20:26.480
Can you imagine me with a gun?

20:29.310 --> 20:31.050
Yeah, I can see it.

20:32.490 --> 20:34.590
One day...

20:34.780 --> 20:37.980
when you've had enough
and you feel like, uh...

20:38.180 --> 20:39.760
ducking out.

20:41.500 --> 20:43.200
Maybe when I'm dead and gone

20:43.400 --> 20:45.370
and you got nobody
and you never will.

20:46.500 --> 20:48.240
I could imagine that.

20:51.290 --> 20:52.720
But you wouldn't, would you?

20:53.860 --> 20:55.350
'Cause you're too good.

20:55.540 --> 20:57.510
♪

21:00.210 --> 21:02.220
Say, give me
one of those cigarettes.

21:02.420 --> 21:04.270
What have you got, Old Gold?

21:04.470 --> 21:05.700
No.

21:05.900 --> 21:07.260
I like Old Gold.

21:10.570 --> 21:12.090
I know.

21:13.660 --> 21:15.700
♪

21:37.070 --> 21:39.290
♪

22:06.410 --> 22:08.060
[door creaks open]

22:09.580 --> 22:12.280
[footsteps echoing]

22:13.850 --> 22:15.290
Oopsie.

22:16.240 --> 22:17.640
Do you need any help?

22:17.840 --> 22:18.690
Uh, no, I'm okay.

22:18.890 --> 22:20.170
Just butterfingers.

22:20.370 --> 22:22.260
[chuckles]
You should see me.

22:22.460 --> 22:23.900
I'm a total klutz.

22:29.780 --> 22:30.960
Oh, right.

22:31.160 --> 22:33.310
Lee Polk.

22:33.510 --> 22:35.830
That's not something
you see every day.

22:38.260 --> 22:41.010
Yeah, it's pretty bad.

22:43.180 --> 22:45.100
Bedtime reading?

22:46.060 --> 22:47.970
I was just doing some filing.

22:51.230 --> 22:52.840
That's some show yesterday.

22:54.150 --> 22:55.420
They do it every year.

22:55.620 --> 22:59.200
I'd call that
cruel and unusual punishment.

23:01.290 --> 23:03.330
[coughing]

23:05.470 --> 23:08.000
Sorry. I don't usually smoke.

23:08.200 --> 23:09.610
It's a nasty habit.

23:09.810 --> 23:11.220
That's why I like it.

23:11.420 --> 23:12.740
Not very becoming
of a lady, though.

23:12.940 --> 23:14.880
Turns your teeth yellow.

23:15.080 --> 23:16.570
See? [chuckles]

23:16.770 --> 23:18.660
That's cigarettes and coffee.

23:18.860 --> 23:20.190
And red wine.

23:20.380 --> 23:23.140
No, your teeth are perfect.

23:26.490 --> 23:28.190
I don't drink coffee,

23:28.390 --> 23:30.530
so my teeth
should be fine, but...

23:31.580 --> 23:32.940
...they're all rotted

23:33.140 --> 23:35.290
due to my extreme propensity
for sweets.

23:35.490 --> 23:37.770
A propensity for sweets.

23:37.970 --> 23:39.800
You don't get enough sweetness
in your life?

23:41.240 --> 23:43.080
I just eat a lot of candy.

23:43.280 --> 23:45.080
Mm. I wouldn't know it
to look at you.

23:45.280 --> 23:46.390
You're so petite.

23:46.590 --> 23:48.390
Being tall has its advantages,
of course,

23:48.590 --> 23:51.560
but most men
are just too short for me.

23:52.900 --> 23:54.920
Have you noticed,
or am I imagining things,

23:55.120 --> 23:58.440
that men these days are
getting shorter and shorter,

23:58.640 --> 24:00.830
balder, and fatter?

24:01.030 --> 24:03.180
All the men around here
are little boys.

24:04.530 --> 24:05.620
You're funny.

24:05.820 --> 24:07.710
I meant outside this prison.

24:07.910 --> 24:08.760
Although you're right.

24:08.960 --> 24:11.110
The guards, the warden,

24:11.310 --> 24:12.670
they're not much to look at.

24:12.870 --> 24:14.760
You should have seen Dr. Frye.

24:14.960 --> 24:17.500
He was really
pretty nasty looking.

24:17.700 --> 24:19.290
That doesn't surprise me.

24:19.490 --> 24:20.460
My office isn't very becoming,

24:20.660 --> 24:22.380
and it all smells
of dirty leather.

24:22.580 --> 24:24.120
I'm beginning to wonder
what went on in there.

24:24.320 --> 24:26.590
Nothing good.

24:28.460 --> 24:31.210
I mean, I never actually
been in that office.

24:31.410 --> 24:34.000
Oh. Well, you should
come by sometime.

24:34.200 --> 24:36.170
Although if the door's closed,

24:36.370 --> 24:38.440
that means
I'm with one of the boys.

24:38.640 --> 24:40.000
Okay.

24:40.950 --> 24:42.400
Aren't you ever scared

24:42.600 --> 24:44.620
being alone in there with them?

24:44.820 --> 24:46.350
No.

24:47.790 --> 24:49.450
Come by, and see me sometime,
all right?

24:49.650 --> 24:51.230
Although, you know, if you
hear me screaming in there,

24:51.430 --> 24:53.060
feel free to kick down the door
and rescue me.

24:53.260 --> 24:54.490
Okay.

24:55.490 --> 24:56.500
I'm just kidding, honey.

24:56.700 --> 24:57.930
There's a buzzer.

25:06.020 --> 25:07.680
[chuckles softly]

25:09.150 --> 25:11.200
[overlapping chatter]

25:13.860 --> 25:15.900
[phones ringing]

25:38.230 --> 25:40.270
- [gate clanks shut]
- [buzzer sounds]

25:44.970 --> 25:47.020
[overlapping chatter]

25:53.240 --> 25:55.550
I'm here to see Leonard Polk.

25:57.510 --> 25:58.810
Anne Polk.

26:03.470 --> 26:04.830
You're not on the schedule.

26:05.030 --> 26:06.220
Are you a late addition?

26:06.420 --> 26:08.910
[buzzer sounds]

26:11.870 --> 26:13.270
I-I was called.

26:13.470 --> 26:15.400
I don't know, I-I'm here now.

26:15.600 --> 26:17.410
Well, you need
to fill out a form.

26:17.610 --> 26:19.090
[handcuffs clicking]

26:20.360 --> 26:21.880
Aren't you Chief Dunlop's kid?

26:22.840 --> 26:24.020
Yeah.

26:24.220 --> 26:25.370
I thought so.

26:25.570 --> 26:27.020
[door opens]

26:27.220 --> 26:28.590
Mrs. Polk? I'm Dr. St. John.

26:28.790 --> 26:30.900
We spoke on the phone.
Thank you so much for coming.

26:31.100 --> 26:32.030
Oh, no need
to bother with that.

26:32.230 --> 26:34.030
We all know who you are.

26:34.230 --> 26:36.200
♪

26:37.590 --> 26:39.430
REBECCA: Eileen, would you
help us with the door?

26:39.630 --> 26:40.780
Thank you.

26:40.980 --> 26:42.860
- [keys jingling]
- It's this way.

26:44.640 --> 26:45.950
Take your coat?

26:46.990 --> 26:48.340
REBECCA:
Please.

26:49.340 --> 26:50.650
Thank you, Eileen.

26:54.560 --> 26:55.870
After you.

26:59.700 --> 27:01.750
♪

27:04.750 --> 27:06.790
[Rebecca speaks indistinctly]

27:08.100 --> 27:10.410
[Anne speaks indistinctly]

27:14.060 --> 27:15.770
ANNE:
Why are you doing this to me?

27:15.970 --> 27:18.810
[continues indistinctly]

27:20.850 --> 27:22.460
[Anne continues indistinctly]

27:25.510 --> 27:27.860
[Anne speaks indistinctly]

27:31.380 --> 27:33.390
ANNE:
Huh?

27:33.590 --> 27:35.390
You got something to say to me?

27:37.260 --> 27:38.650
[Anne continues indistinctly]

27:42.260 --> 27:43.970
♪

27:44.170 --> 27:45.920
[speaking indistinctly]

27:46.750 --> 27:47.840
ANNE:
Let me out!

27:48.040 --> 27:50.110
Let me out! Let me out!

27:50.310 --> 27:52.680
Let me out!

27:52.870 --> 27:55.290
[keys jingling]

27:55.490 --> 27:57.980
Y-You do... y'all do
what you want with him.

27:58.180 --> 28:00.200
Won't even talk
to his own mother?

28:00.400 --> 28:02.210
He's always been a nasty boy.

28:02.410 --> 28:04.990
A filthy, nasty boy!

28:05.190 --> 28:07.120
RANDY:
I need to lock up.

28:08.860 --> 28:11.740
Visitation hours were
actually over 20 minutes ago.

28:11.940 --> 28:13.250
REBECCA:
Oh, I-I understand.

28:14.950 --> 28:17.350
Would you like to keep talking
in my office?

28:17.550 --> 28:18.520
[handcuffs clinking]

28:21.480 --> 28:23.230
- Let's go.
- Turn around.

28:23.430 --> 28:24.580
Oh, no.
That won't be necessary.

28:24.780 --> 28:26.220
- I need to cuff him.
- No.

28:31.360 --> 28:33.140
Don't worry, Lee.
It's all right.

28:41.370 --> 28:42.980
[mocking]:
That won't be necessary.

28:44.110 --> 28:45.950
Don't do that. She's a doctor.

28:46.150 --> 28:47.210
I think she needs a doctor.

28:47.410 --> 28:48.250
That kid killed a cop.

28:48.450 --> 28:50.210
He killed his father.

28:50.410 --> 28:51.470
There's a difference.

28:51.670 --> 28:53.070
[Randy chuckles]

28:55.640 --> 28:58.210
REBECCA [muffled]: Oh, I'm so
sorry. Let me see who it is.

28:59.340 --> 29:00.220
Oh, Eileen.

29:00.420 --> 29:02.520
Um, can I help you?

29:04.830 --> 29:06.310
You forgot your notebook.

29:06.510 --> 29:07.970
Oh, thank you so much.

29:08.170 --> 29:09.270
I actually need this.

29:09.470 --> 29:11.190
Um, hope you didn't read it.

29:11.390 --> 29:12.710
- No, of course not.
- Oh, no,

29:12.910 --> 29:14.700
I'm just kidding.
It's just chicken scratch.

29:18.400 --> 29:19.590
[door opens]

29:19.790 --> 29:20.930
Wait. Eileen.

29:24.320 --> 29:25.770
I don't mean to be forward,

29:25.970 --> 29:27.940
and, um, you probably
have other plans already,

29:28.140 --> 29:30.210
but, um, can I take you
to a drink tonight?

29:30.410 --> 29:31.950
I don't know anyone
in this darn town,

29:32.150 --> 29:33.990
and I'd love to treat you
to a cocktail if you're game.

29:34.190 --> 29:35.690
- Okay.
- Okay?

29:35.890 --> 29:37.040
- I've twisted your arm?
- [chuckles]

29:37.240 --> 29:40.430
So, uh, who makes
the best martini in town?

29:40.630 --> 29:42.350
- Maybe O'Hara's?
- O'Hara's.

29:42.550 --> 29:43.740
It's actually
the only bar in town.

29:43.940 --> 29:45.000
No, O'Hara's is good.

29:45.200 --> 29:47.490
See you at 7:00?

29:47.680 --> 29:49.270
With bells on?
Is that the expression?

29:49.470 --> 29:51.400
- [chuckles]
- [door opens]

29:51.600 --> 29:53.060
[door closes]

29:53.260 --> 29:54.920
["I'll Take Care of You"
by Bobby "Blue" Bland playing]

29:56.920 --> 30:00.930
♪ I know you've been hurt

30:01.130 --> 30:02.890
Ah!

30:03.090 --> 30:05.360
- ♪ By someone else
- [groans]

30:07.060 --> 30:10.330
♪ I can tell by the way

30:10.530 --> 30:13.550
♪ You carry yourself

30:14.500 --> 30:17.430
♪ But if you let me

30:17.630 --> 30:20.860
♪ Here's what I'll do

30:21.860 --> 30:26.050
♪ I'll take care of you

30:26.250 --> 30:31.480
♪ I... I've loved and lost

30:32.910 --> 30:35.650
♪ The same as you

30:36.920 --> 30:40.360
♪ So you see, I know

30:40.560 --> 30:43.660
♪ Just what
you've been through ♪

30:44.660 --> 30:48.330
♪ But if you'll let me

30:48.530 --> 30:51.810
♪ Here's what I'll do

30:52.010 --> 30:55.980
♪ Oh, I just got
to take care of you ♪

30:57.240 --> 31:01.860
♪ You won't ever
have to worry ♪

31:05.820 --> 31:12.560
♪ You won't ever have to cry

31:15.170 --> 31:19.920
♪ For I'll be there
beside you ♪

31:21.920 --> 31:28.060
♪ To dry your weeping eyes

31:28.260 --> 31:30.850
♪ So, darling

31:31.050 --> 31:34.160
♪ Tell me

31:34.360 --> 31:38.160
♪ That you'll be true

31:38.360 --> 31:40.600
[fading]:
♪ For there is no doubt...

31:40.800 --> 31:43.640
[crowd chattering]

31:43.840 --> 31:45.810
♪

31:48.860 --> 31:49.960
- Hi.
- Oh, Eileen.

31:50.160 --> 31:51.440
Hi.

31:51.630 --> 31:52.650
Please, please, please, sit.

31:52.850 --> 31:54.530
Um, what are you having?

31:54.720 --> 31:57.960
Uh, I'll have a beer, I guess.

31:58.160 --> 31:59.530
A beer? Oh. [chuckles]

31:59.730 --> 32:00.840
Hi, Eileen.

32:01.040 --> 32:01.920
Good to see you, hon.

32:02.120 --> 32:04.060
What's next, sweetheart?

32:04.260 --> 32:06.490
Um, well... Oh, my stars.

32:06.690 --> 32:08.190
You're absolutely frozen.

32:08.390 --> 32:10.500
Um, one beer, please,
and maybe a little whiskey

32:10.700 --> 32:13.010
to warm up my girl.
What say, huh?

32:14.540 --> 32:16.630
My, you look very glamorous.

32:16.830 --> 32:17.850
It's just an old dress.

32:18.050 --> 32:19.060
May I?

32:26.030 --> 32:28.730
SANDY: How about you,
sweetheart? Another martini?

32:28.930 --> 32:30.170
Love one. Thank you.

32:30.370 --> 32:32.740
Maybe let's hold the olives
this time.

32:32.940 --> 32:34.700
I thought I'd have
a hard time finding this place,

32:34.900 --> 32:36.430
but here it is. [chuckles]

32:41.870 --> 32:43.520
You feeling all right?

32:45.000 --> 32:47.710
Yeah, I'm fine. [chuckles]

32:47.910 --> 32:49.360
Uh, there's something wrong
with my car,

32:49.560 --> 32:51.320
so I have to drive
with the windows down,

32:51.520 --> 32:53.150
or else it fills with smoke.

32:53.350 --> 32:54.500
- [chuckles]
- Oh, you're kidding.

32:54.700 --> 32:56.240
That sounds absolutely awful.

32:56.440 --> 32:59.110
Can't you get your husband
to fix that for you?

32:59.310 --> 33:01.240
Oh, no, I'm not married.

33:01.440 --> 33:03.120
I've always been single.

33:03.320 --> 33:04.770
And when I do
have a guy around,

33:04.970 --> 33:06.810
it's just for fun,
and it's brief.

33:07.010 --> 33:10.120
No, I never stay anywhere
long with anything.

33:10.320 --> 33:12.340
Sort of my modus vivendi

33:12.540 --> 33:16.380
or my pathology, depending on
who I'm talking to.

33:18.820 --> 33:21.180
How long have you
worked at Moorehead?

33:21.380 --> 33:23.000
Three or four years.

33:24.300 --> 33:26.700
Uh, it was only
supposed to be temporary,

33:26.900 --> 33:30.930
while I moved back for a bit
while my mother was sick,

33:31.130 --> 33:33.320
and then she died, so...

33:33.520 --> 33:36.240
I've been at the prison,
and time's just flown by.

33:36.440 --> 33:37.720
Oh, God.

33:37.910 --> 33:39.980
Prison is no place
for time to fly by.

33:40.180 --> 33:42.410
And your mother dying.

33:45.020 --> 33:46.990
That's a lot for a young lady.

33:47.190 --> 33:50.600
Ah. 24.

33:50.800 --> 33:53.770
Then you must be eager
to get back out there. Are you?

33:56.330 --> 33:59.780
You know, um,
I'm an orphan, too.

33:59.980 --> 34:01.570
My uncle raised me out West.

34:01.760 --> 34:04.220
[chuckles]
Where the sun shines.

34:04.420 --> 34:06.000
I don't understand
how you all do it here,

34:06.200 --> 34:07.610
winter after winter.

34:07.810 --> 34:10.100
It's positively creepy.
I don't know.

34:10.300 --> 34:12.360
I'm in a sort of strange
love affair with New England.

34:12.560 --> 34:14.660
I love it, but I also hate it.

34:16.480 --> 34:18.530
Things feel very real here,
don't they?

34:19.570 --> 34:21.710
Sort of there's no...

34:22.930 --> 34:24.110
...imagination.

34:24.310 --> 34:26.850
There's no sentimentality
or fantasy.

34:27.050 --> 34:30.190
There's... there's just
nowhere to hide.

34:34.500 --> 34:36.250
Sorry.

34:36.450 --> 34:38.170
I've had too much to drink.

34:38.370 --> 34:40.390
I tend to talk when I've had
too much to drink.

34:40.590 --> 34:41.780
It's all right.

34:41.980 --> 34:43.170
Mm, it's better
than talking too little.

34:43.370 --> 34:45.090
[chuckles]

34:45.290 --> 34:46.860
Did you see Lee Polk today?

34:49.470 --> 34:50.350
Uh...

34:50.550 --> 34:51.920
Did she say anything to you?

34:52.120 --> 34:53.870
Mrs. Polk?

34:54.830 --> 34:57.060
She was just upset.

34:57.260 --> 34:59.540
Those mothers are always upset.

34:59.740 --> 35:01.840
Mm-hmm.

35:02.040 --> 35:04.360
Did she seem
like an angry woman to you?

35:05.530 --> 35:07.760
I don't know. Uh...

35:07.960 --> 35:09.240
everyone's kind of angry here.

35:09.440 --> 35:10.930
- It's Massachusetts.
- Mm.

35:12.110 --> 35:15.250
Well, I had this professor
at Harvard.

35:15.450 --> 35:18.250
He was brilliant,
but very difficult.

35:18.450 --> 35:22.520
Uh, he did this--
these experiments on prisoners

35:22.720 --> 35:24.740
studying the effects
of psychedelics on recidivism.

35:24.930 --> 35:26.000
Now, I don't agree
with his methods,

35:26.200 --> 35:27.260
there is no magic pill,

35:27.460 --> 35:30.990
but... but you can
set people free...

35:32.430 --> 35:36.440
...if you can get them to tell
the truth, to feel it.

35:36.640 --> 35:38.220
That's what I want to do.

35:40.090 --> 35:41.270
Secrets and lies.

35:41.470 --> 35:43.570
I tell you, doll...

35:44.830 --> 35:47.190
...some families are so sick,
so twisted,

35:47.390 --> 35:48.890
the only way out's
for someone to die.

35:49.090 --> 35:50.530
Don't you think?

35:51.880 --> 35:53.840
PAT: Hey! What'd you say
your name was?

35:54.580 --> 35:55.720
Who, me?

35:55.920 --> 35:57.720
Ah, yeah. W-We was just saying

35:57.920 --> 35:59.200
that you look so familiar.

35:59.400 --> 36:01.030
Are you in the movies
or something?

36:01.230 --> 36:02.690
Hardly. I work
at the boys' prison.

36:02.890 --> 36:03.820
- Ah.
- I'm Eileen,

36:04.020 --> 36:04.990
and this is my friend, Rebecca.

36:05.190 --> 36:06.680
She's a psychologist.

36:07.860 --> 36:08.870
Don't be shy, Rebecca.

36:09.070 --> 36:10.040
These boys won't bite.

36:10.240 --> 36:13.610
Not unless you ask us to.
[laughs]

36:13.810 --> 36:15.350
